						"url": "{{base_url}}/api/v1/monitors/{{monitor_id}}/metrics/query",
						"description": "Query metrics with dynamic filters and advanced filtering capabilities.\n\n**Purpose:**\nThis endpoint allows you to query metrics with fine-grained control over time ranges, metric groups, and tag-based filtering. It's designed for flexible metric retrieval with support for complex filtering scenarios.\n\n**Supported Operators:**\n- `eq` - Equals (exact match)\n- `in` - In list (matches any value in the provided array)\n- `like` - SQL LIKE pattern matching (% wildcards supported)\n- `exists` - Tag key exists (values array can be empty)\n- `gt` - Greater than (numeric comparison)\n- `lt` - Less than (numeric comparison)\n- `gte` - Greater than or equal to (numeric comparison)\n- `lte` - Less than or equal to (numeric comparison)\n\n**Parameters:**\n- `start` (required): ISO 8601 timestamp for query start time\n- `end` (required): ISO 8601 timestamp for query end time\n- `metric_groups` (optional): Array of metric group names to filter by (e.g., [\"host.cpu\", \"host.memory\"])\n- `tag_filters` (optional): Array of tag filter objects with `key`, `op`, and `values` fields\n- `limit` (optional): Maximum number of metrics to return (default: 100, max: 1000)\n- `latest` (optional): If true, returns only the most recent metric per metric_group (default: false)\n\n**Example Use Cases:**\n1. Get all CPU metrics for specific cores: Use `op: \"in\"` with core IDs\n2. Get metrics for a specific type: Use `op: \"eq\"` for exact match\n3. Get metrics where a tag exists: Use `op: \"exists\"`\n4. Get metrics with numeric filtering: Use `op: \"gt\"`, `\"lt\"`, `\"gte\"`, or `\"lte\"`\n5. Get latest metrics only: Set `latest: true`"
